- Styx: Greatest Hits: Styx’s strongest alignment with my tastes is their theatrical/prog lean and bold dynamic contrasts — qualities I said I appreciate when richly produced. However, Styx’s greatest‑hits character is explicitly tied to strong multi‑part vocal harmonies and a polished, harmony‑forward commercial sheen. That runs counter to my dislike of “slick, poppy multi‑part harmonies and choir gloss over emotional depth.” In addition, the description of Styx as punchy and curated for CD listening does not mention the warm, analogue, piano‑forward traits or substantive liner notes that I prize; the emphasis on vocal harmonies makes this release riskier against my specific dislikes.
Choice justification:
- I chose Elton John — Greatest Hits 1976–86 because its core attributes (piano‑driven arrangements, warm analogue mastering and informative liner notes) map more closely to the concrete production and documentation details I value. While neither candidate is a concept, album‑length prog narrative (my top ideal), Elton’s emphasis on piano and warm, well‑documented production compensates better for the compilation format and promises the kind of repeatable, detail‑rich CD listening experience I prefer.
- I rejected Styx because, despite their theatrical and prog leanings, the greatest‑hits framing foregrounds lush multi‑part vocal harmonies and a polished pop sheen — exactly the “slick, poppy multi‑part harmonies/choir gloss” I said I dislike. The Styx compilation therefore presents a stronger conflict with my stated dislikes than the Elton John compilation does with my preferences.

